      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA342-kiḷavi">1. itu kuṟainērnta tōḻi talaimakaḷai mukampukka taṉ coṟ kēḷātu viṭali ṉiṟappa vāṟṟāṉ āyiṉāṉeṉa vuṇarntāṟṟāḷāyt taṉṉuḷḷē colliyatu.
            2. talaimakaṉukkuk kuṟainērnta tōḻi talaimakaḷai mukampukkallāḷā yāṟṟātu taṉṉuḷḷē colliyatūumām.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">1. This is what the confidante, who had granted [HIS] request, said, in order to seek favour with HER, to her own heart, being unable to bear it when perceiving that he had become unable to bear it when he begged because he had been sent off without his word being heard.
            2. It is also what the confidante, wo had granted HIS request, said to her own heart when unable to bear it, seeking favour with HER.</p>
        </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA342">
<l>            māveṉa matittu maṭalūrn tāṅku</l>
<l>            matileṉa matittu veṇṭē rēṟi</l>
<l>            yeṉvāy niṉmoḻi māṭṭē ṉiṉvayiṟ</l>
<l>            cēri cērā varuvōrk keṉṟu</l>
<l>            maruḷal vēṇṭu maṉpuṭai yōyeṉak</l>
<l>            kaṇṇiṉi tākak kōṭṭiyun tēralaḷ</l>
<l>            yāṉē yelvaḷai yātta kāṉal</l>
<l>            vaṇṭu ṇaṟuvī nuṇṇitiṉ varitta</l>
<l>            ceṉṉic cēvaṭi cērtti</l>
<l>            ṉeṉṉeṉap paṭumō veṉṟalu muṇṭē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>            “It is necessary to be considerate, you who have love,</l>
<l>            to the one who always comes on your behalf, without joining [our] quarter.</l>
<l>             I cannot [convey to him?] your words with my mouth,</l>
<l>            he mounted on [his] white chariot,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">veṇṭēr</term>: here tradition wants to read a "mirage" (HE being already close to the state of delirium), but that does not really make sense. You mount a chariot and not a mirage. I rather think he is still coming with the chariot, but threatens to be driven to the utmost, that is, riding the palmyra horse.</note> taking it as a fortification,</l>
<l>            as if he were mounting the palmyra stems, taking them for a horse.”</l>
<l>        – although [I] bow to be pleasing to the eye, she does not understand.</l>
<l>        There is also [her]<note place="foot">The Tamil might well be read as a single sentence construction (<term xml:lang="ta">tēralaḷ</term> as an unmarked genitive and agent of <term xml:lang="ta">eṉṟal</term>). On the other hand, there is the -<term xml:lang="ta">ē</term> with <term xml:lang="ta">yāṉē</term>. If this is more than a metrical filler, it might mark the beginning of a new sentence, awkward all the more since it is not subject of the main clause, but perhaps of the absolutive <term xml:lang="ta">cērtti</term>.</note> saying: “what is going on?”,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">eṉ eṉa paṭumō</term>: here the <term xml:lang="ta">eṉa</term> in this strange formulaic question obviously has to be interpreted not along with the <term xml:lang="ta">paṭum</term> as a passive (cf. KT 194 + n.), but as a kind of rhetorical emphasis on the <term xml:lang="ta">eṉ</term>, not unlike the occurrences with ideophones.</note></l>
<l>            if I, for one, join to [her] red feet [my] head</l>
<l>            lined finely with fragrant blossoms eaten by bees</l>
<l>            from the seashore grove bound with light bangles<note place="foot">Bangles in the hair? Otherwise how to connect the <term xml:lang="ta">yātta</term>?</note>?</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
